On display 3 at 21:42, the Codex app was open to project `mac-hub`, chat `Plan MacBook housekeeping`. The user had asked why rebooting the Mac mini was needed, and Codex explained that the reboot was a persistence/readiness test rather than a repair. It listed checks that would prove hub readiness after a reboot: SSH/Remote Login, Tailscale/network identity, NAS/SMB/Time Machine destination reconnect, backup/list/restore ability, `ks2-mastery` repo/toolchain/auth, encrypted vault access, and session/cache independence. Codex also noted that Time Machine was copying and said it would wait for idle to avoid interrupting backup.

The user then asked to skip reboot and do the rest. Codex responded that it would run a live readiness gate without reboot and report SSH, Tailscale, NAS/SMB, Time Machine, GitHub, Wrangler, secret vault, `ks2-mastery`, checkout/build/deploy dry-run status. It reported running non-disruptive checks. It found SSH, Tailscale IP, NAS mounts, GitHub auth, git remote read, and Wrangler OAuth were OK. It also found the Time Machine copy phase completed, with latest completed backup `2026-07-04-224034.backup`, and Time Machine in `ThinningPostBackup` cleanup.

Codex then described a first secret-vault restore proof attempt hitting a shell quoting issue where `awk $1` was interpreted by zsh as a positional parameter. It said it reran with safer quoting/hash parsing and checked the mount manually. It then reported that vault restore proof passed, SHA matched `.env`, and no secret was printed. It kept `ks2-mastery` behind a live dry-run gate and used `npm run check` to confirm the Mac mini was OK for repo/build/worker/Cloudflare dry-run.

By 21:44, Codex reported dry-run success, with a generated file `worker/src/generated-build-version.js` restored afterwards to keep the Mac mini worktree clean. It later reported Time Machine idle with `Running = 0`. Codex said it updated the plan and ledger to include Time Machine idle state, the no-reboot readiness gate, vault proof rerun, and `npm run check` rerun, with `delete_allowed` staying `no` because skipping reboot meant the MacBook source copy was not yet fully retired. It showed two edited files: `docs/plans/macbook-housekeeping-migration-ledger-2026-07-02.tsv` and `docs/plans/macbook-housekeeping-phase0-audit-2026-07-02.md`.

