### Roguecardv2 generated asset spike

On display 2 at 21:42, Cursor was open in repo `roguecardv2` with a chat titled `Game asset creation plan` and an editor tab for `Generated Asset Pipeline Plan`. The user had asked whether they could do an experiment to cut out a generated character from a spritesheet, then test assembly, rather than cutting out the prompt. Cursor/Codex responded with a plan for a spike before the main pipeline. The user typed “approve the spike”, and the agent switched to Agent Mode, stating that the user approved the cutout spike and that it needed to create scratch files, run image generation, and build the test rig.

The visible plan was titled `Spirebound 生成式 Asset 計劃 (Generated Asset Pipeline)`. Goals included using Codex CLI image generation through `tools/imagen.sh` with `gpt-image-2` to generate illuminated stained-glass painterly raster assets, supporting animated sprites, and maintaining a fallback to procedural SVG. The architecture section described a manifest-driven resolver using `public/assets/manifest.json`, lookup through `art.js`, and falling back to existing SVG when no raster asset exists. It referenced asset directories like `public/assets/enemies`, `heroes`, `cards`, `props`, `potions`, `events`, and `title`.

The plan described animation strategies: Tier A living-state PNG plus runtime CSS/JS rig with breathing/scale/skew, hover-float, glow pulse, and optional eye/fire layers; Tier B sprite sheet through `tools/sheet.mjs`; Tier C layered parallax for title screen only. It also listed existing coupling points: `crackSvg()`, `v.shatter()` in `src/vfx.js`, `rigCombatants()` in `src/ui.js`, and UI icons/map nodes/relic/status glyphs remaining procedural/vector.

The spike plan before Phase 0 was a cutout animation feasibility test. It specified generating 3-4 prompt recipes for a parts sheet containing one hero plus one enemy, trying several recipes: character disassembled for cutout animation, labelled 2x3 grid, edit-chain recipe, and stained-glass lead-line separation. It planned `tools/cutout.mjs` using `sharp` to infer bounding boxes/layout JSON and auto-trim transparent PNGs. It also planned `scratch/cutout-spike/rig.html` with nested divs, transform origins, and CSS keyframes for idle breathing/sway/weapon bob. The go/no-go checklist focused on part completeness, style consistency, joint-line quality, and labour cost compared with recipe reuse.

By 21:43, the agent in Cursor had a to-do list with four spike items: generate 3-4 prompt recipes and parts sheets, build `tools/cutout.mjs`, build the scratch rig with idle animation, and evaluate outputs/go-no-go. It had read `art.js` around lines `266-305` and searched `data.js` for enemy kinds such as `beastknight`.

At 21:48, Cursor’s editor showed generated scratch files in `scratch/cutout-spike/gen`: `a_hero_parts.png`, `c1_hero_full.png`, and `d_hero_leadlines.png`, plus `scratch/cutout-spike/rig.html`. The file tree also showed `tools/cutout.mjs` and `tools/imagen.sh`, with `tools/cutout.mjs`, `package.json`, and `package-lock.json` modified. The displayed image `d_hero_leadlines.png` showed a fantasy stained-glass character split into separate pieces: hood/head, torso, arms, weapon, lower body, and shield/arm pieces. The style used dark blue, purple, gold, and cyan stained-glass panels with lantern motifs.

At 21:50, the editor preview showed `c1_hero_full.png`, a full-body hooded stained-glass fantasy character holding a glowing blue sword and lantern, with a dark hood, blue glowing eyes, blue/purple cloak, and gold frame accents. Cursor’s chat said it had edited two files, explored two files, run a search and six commands, and was monitoring background tasks. It mentioned running recipe D lead-line split and checking alpha channels of generated sheets, then rendering grid overlays for coordinate measuring.

At 21:52, the editor returned to the generated asset plan, still focused on the spike section. Cursor chat showed the agent waiting on or having run background tasks, including alpha-channel checks and grid overlay rendering.

